\fs28 1. Relax and Breathe:
\fs24 \
\
Remember to take deep breaths before going on stage. Relaxing the body and mind helps ease nervousness and allows for clearer expression.\
\

\fs28 2. Connect with the Material:
\fs24 \
\
Connect emotionally with your characters and the story. When you personally resonate with the material, your expressions and emotions become more authentic.\
\

\fs28 3. Project Confidence:
\fs24 \
\
Remember that the audience wants you to succeed. Encourage good posture and confident body language. Confidence in their physical presence can translate into a more convincing performance.\
\

\fs28 4. Speak Clearly and Slow Down:
\fs24 \
\
Emphasize the importance of clear articulation. Speak slowly and enunciate words. This not only improves clarity but also helps convey emotions more effectively.\
\

\fs28 5. Use Facial Expressions:
\fs24 \
\
Remember that facial expressions are powerful tools for conveying emotions. Use your faces to express feelings and thoughts relevant to the scene.\
\

\fs28 6. Practice Vocal Warm-Ups:
\fs24 \
\
Include vocal warm-ups as part of rehearsals. Exercises like tongue twisters and vocal scales can help improve voice clarity and projection.\
\

\fs28 7. Explore Physicality:
\fs24 \
\
Use your bodies to express emotions. Physical movements, gestures, and postures can enhance the overall impact of their performance.\
\

\fs28 8. Listen and React:
\fs24 \
\
It is important to actively listen on stage. React authentically to their scene partners. Genuine reactions create a more natural and engaging performance.\
\

\fs28 9. Rehearse Regularly:
\fs24 \
\
Consistent rehearsal builds confidence. Regular practice helps actors become more familiar with their lines, blocking, and the overall flow of the performance.\
\

\fs28 10. Embrace Mistakes:
\fs24 \
\
Remember that mistakes happen, and they are part of the learning process. Everyone please stay in the moment and continue with the scene, rather than dwelling on errors.\
\

\f1\i\fs28 Celebrate successes, no matter how small, and remember that everyone is learning and growing together. With time and practice, our confidence and comfort on stage will naturally improve.}